# Load dplyr package and the built-in mpg dataset
library(dplyr)

# Create a new variable cty_hwy that sums up cty and hwy
mpg_with_cty_hwy <- mpg %>%
  mutate(cty_hwy = cty + hwy)

# Group by year and calculate the average cty_hwy
result <- mpg_with_cty_hwy %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(avg_cty_hwy = mean(cty_hwy))

# Find the average cty_hwy for the year 1999 and round it to 2 decimal places
avg_cty_hwy_1999 <- round(filter(result, year == 1999)$avg_cty_hwy, 2)

# Print the average cty_hwy for 1999
print(paste("The average cty_hwy for the year 1999 is:", avg_cty_hwy_1999))
[1] "The average cty_hwy for the year 1999 is: 40.44"
# Load the required packages
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Create a boxplot for hwy for each manufacturer
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = manufacturer, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of hwy mileage by Manufacturer",
       x = "Manufacturer",
       y = "Highway Mileage")


# To find the manufacturer with the highest outlier
highest_outlier_manufacturer <- mpg %>%
  group_by(manufacturer) %>%
  summarise(highest_hwy = max(hwy)) %>%
  arrange(desc(highest_hwy)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 1) %>%
  pull(manufacturer)

# Print the manufacturer with the highest outlier in hwy
print(paste("The manufacturer with the outlier of the highest value is:", highest_outlier_manufacturer))
[1] "The manufacturer with the outlier of the highest value is: volkswagen"
